        <chapter xml:id="ch-introduction">
            <title>Introduction</title>
            
            <p>
                Welcome to this sample PreTeXt textbook created with PreTeXt Canvas. 
                This document demonstrates various PreTeXt elements and their usage.
            </p>
            
            <section xml:id="sec-basics">
                <title>Basic Elements</title>
                
                <p>
                    PreTeXt supports various types of content including paragraphs, 
                    lists, mathematical expressions, and structured elements like 
                    theorems and definitions.
                </p>
                
                <subsection xml:id="subsec-lists">
                    <title>Lists and Formatting</title>
                    
                    <p>Here are some examples of different list types:</p>
                    
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Unordered list item one</p></li>
                        <li><p>Unordered list item two</p></li>
                        <li><p>Unordered list item three</p></li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <ol>
                        <li><p>Ordered list item one</p></li>
                        <li><p>Ordered list item two</p></li>
                        <li><p>Ordered list item three</p></li>
                    </ol>
                    
                    <dl>
                        <li>
                            <title>Definition List</title>
                            <p>A list where each item has a term and its definition.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <title>PreTeXt</title>
                            <p>An authoring and publishing system for scholarly documents.</p>
                        </li>
                    </dl>
                </subsection>
            </section>
            
            <section xml:id="sec-mathematics">
                <title>Mathematical Content</title>
                
                <p>
                    PreTeXt has excellent support for mathematical notation using LaTeX syntax. 
                    Here are some examples:
                </p>
                
                <p>
                    Inline mathematics: <m>x^2 + y^2 = z^2</m> and <m>\int_0^1 f(x) \, dx</m>.
                </p>
                
                <p>Display mathematics:</p>
                
                <me>
                    \lim_{n \to \infty} \sum_{k=1}^n \frac{1}{k^2} = \frac{\pi^2}{6}
                </me>
                
                <p>Multi-line display mathematics:</p>
                
                <md>
                    <mrow>f(x) &amp;= x^3 - 3x^2 + 2x - 1</mrow>
                    <mrow>f'(x) &amp;= 3x^2 - 6x + 2</mrow>
                    <mrow>f''(x) &amp;= 6x - 6</mrow>
                </md>
                
                <definition xml:id="def-continuous">
                    <title>Continuous Function</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            A function <m>f: \R \to \R</m> is <term>continuous</term> at a point 
                            <m>a \in \R</m> if for every <m>\epsilon > 0</m>, there exists 
                            <m>\delta > 0</m> such that for all <m>x \in \R</m> with 
                            <m>|x - a| &lt; \delta</m>, we have <m>|f(x) - f(a)| &lt; \epsilon</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                </definition>
                
                <theorem xml:id="thm-intermediate-value">
                    <title>Intermediate Value Theorem</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>f: [a,b] \to \R</m> be a continuous function. If <m>y</m> 
                            is any value between <m>f(a)</m> and <m>f(b)</m>, then there exists 
                            <m>c \in [a,b]</m> such that <m>f(c) = y</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <proof>
                        <p>
                            This follows from the completeness of the real numbers and the 
                            definition of continuity. The detailed proof is left as an exercise.
                        </p>
                    </proof>
                </theorem>
            </section>
        </chapter>
        
